@{b}About this FAQ@{ub}

   This FAQ was created after I noticed that there was a need for it in the
comp.sys.amiga.emulation newsgroup. Since I've had a Bridgeboard for a while
and know how to utilise it to its fullest, I've decided to create this FAQ

@{b}What this FAQ is:@{ub}

This FAQ will provide general information about Bridgeboards, provide
solutions for common problems, as well as providing the reader with information
on the different utilities that exist for Bridgeboards. It is also to archive
any pertinent and useful information that appears from time to time on the
comp.sys.amiga.emulation newsgroup.

@{b}What this FAQ is NOT:@{ub}

It is not meant to replace the manual(s) that came with the Bridgeboard, nor is it
meant to provide instructions on the use/installation of the Bridgeboard and/or the
software it includes, or of other utilities mentioned in this FAQ.

   To send me any contributions, corrections or suggestions,  please see @{"Contacting The Author" link "author" }.
@endnode

@node "WhatIs" "What is a Bridgeboard?"
@toc "main"
@next "whatare"
@prev "disclaimer"

@{b}   What is a Bridgeboard?@{ub}

A Bridgeboard is an Amiga specific card with a 8088 or X86 series CPU that allows 
running PC software as well as sharing of the resources of the Amiga (monitor, disks,
keyboard and mouse, etc...) with the PC.

The Bridgeboards are not very fast by today's PC standards, but some can still be upgraded
to faster processors. They are also much faster than software-only 680x0 based emulators, but
with the advent of PowerPC processors and emulators based around these processors, this hardware
solution may become a dying breed.

They do still provide a good performance for those who can't afford PowerPC upgrades, but need 
PC compatibility at a good speed, without having to buy a complete PC system.

@endnode

@node "WhatAre" "What are the Bridgeboards"
@next "xtbb"
@prev "whatis"
@toc "main"

@{b} What are the Bridgeboards?@{ub}

        @{"A2088 XT Bridgeboard" link "XTBB" } @{"Picture" system "sys:utilities/multiview a2088.iff"}

This was the first Bridgeboard made. It is based off the Intel 8088 CPU, which
is an 8-bit version of the 8086 CPU found in most XT compatible computers.
Fully compatible with the 8086 it will run any software for the XT class of
machines. The A8088 bridgeboard came standard with a 4.77MHz CPU, 512K of RAM,
Monochrome/CGA display and a 360K 5.25" disk drive.

        

        @{"A2286 AT Bridgeboard" link "286BB" } @{"Picture" system "sys:utilities/multiview a2286.iff"}

This was the second Bridgeboard that was made. It is based off the Intel 20286
chip found in any AT compatible computer system. It came standard with an 8MHz
CPU, 1MB of RAM, Monochrome/CGA display and a 1.2MB 5.25" disk drive.



        @{"A2386SX Bridgeboard" link "386BB" } @{"Picture" system "sys:utilities/multiview a2386.iff"}

This was the last Bridgeboard made. There are three versions of it, all are
based off the 80386SX chip. This chip differs in that it is internally a
32-bit chip, but it only has a 16-bit bus (like the 68000). All A2386SX
Bridgeboards came standard with a 16MHz/20MHz/25MHz CPU, 1MB of RAM (up to 8MB
on board), Monochrome/CGA graphics, and they could share your Amiga 3.5" disk
drive.


@endnode

@node "XTBB" "A2088 XT Bridgeboard"
@prev "whatare"
@next "286bb"
